Section section_02 (Chars 9138–12778):
Section Summary: In his later years, Herbert Spencer was disheartened to see that his social and political doctrines were not widely accepted by a new generation of thinkers. Despite this, he had established a respected position in the philosophy of life and mind. Spencer's philosophy emphasized the concept of evolution as a universal principle, governed by natural laws and processes, which he believed could explain all phenomena, including the growth of society and individual life. He argued that everything, including mental evolution, could be interpreted in terms of matter, motion, and force, with the ultimate goal of unified knowledge. Spencer's philosophy ultimately acknowledged the limits of human understanding, recognizing that some mysteries, such as the nature of consciousness, may be beyond human comprehension.
